<HEADLINE> Drop of AIDS Deaths Coincides with New Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 9 (Xinhua) -- AIDS deaths in California
during the first half of 1997 dropped by 60 percent to 1,112 from
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The decline coincided with the widespread of protease
inhibitors, the newest anti-viral drugs. Researchers say that
California's aggressive attempts to distribute the drugs to
infected patients appear to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
California's AIDS Drug Assistance Program provides the drugs
free, or at limited cost, to those with adjusted gross incomes of
less than 50,000 U.S. dollars a year. The drug treatment could
cost as much as 12,000 dollars a year for HIV-positive people.
</P>
<P>
Amid all the optimism, researchers caution that the lifesaving
effect of protease drugs may not last and the virus may return.
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
