<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies US Claims of Executing Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today dismissed as
unfounded U.S. claims that it had received confirmed reports
about Iraq's execution of a group of political prisoners, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The INA quoted a government spokesman as saying that the
U.S. government had been shedding crocodile tears for human rights
in Iraq, though it is responsible for the death of hundreds of
thousands of Iraqis and for denying 22 million people the most
basic rights to subsistence.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was responding to a Voice of America (VOA)
report representing views of the U.S. government, which listed
5,000 Iranian POWs, 600 Kuwaiti POWs and 200,000 Kurds as
unaccounted-for.
</P>
<P>
The VOA report was intended to mar the image of Iraq for its
defiance of U.S. aggression, arrogance and disregard of
international law, said the spokesman, adding that neither Iran
nor the Iraqi Kurds had asked for U.S. intervention.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the spokesman said, the figures mentioned in the
VOA report are unreal and unsubstantiated by any neutral
international party.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that such repeated allegations were
expressive of a sense of bitterness and disappointment at the
White House due to its utter failure of a campaign to rally Arab,
Western and international support for its military action against
Iraq and prolonged sanctions against its people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
