<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Gum to Heart Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- There may be a direct casual
link between gum disease and heart disease, British researchers
said today.
</P>
<P>
Evidence of the link appears to be strongest in men aged 40 to
50, according to a study published in the British Dental Journal.
</P>
<P>
Poor oral health may be as a significant heart disease risk
factor alongside smoking and a fatty diet, the study suggested.
</P>
<P>
The most likely explanation for the link is that bacteria
produced as a result of gum disease have an effect on clotting
mechanisms in the blood which increase the risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
People who have an over-reactive natural body defense system
could be more sensitive to the effects of the bacteria,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
However, they stressed that it still needs further confirmation
although evidence of the link is mounting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
