<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Considers Russia's Early WTO Membership Impossible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
held little hope about Russia's joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO) at an early date, saying it could take years.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive body noted that Russia had
submitted no offers to the WTO, the Geneva-based trade watchdog,
since 1993 when it sent its application to WTO's predecessor, the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, says the European Report,
a EU newsletter published here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This has been a great disappointment for WTO members, who had
themselves intensified work over the past years in response to a
Russian request to accelerate the work program, the commission
said.
</P>
<P>
One of the problems with Russia's application was that Moscow
was not prepared to make any "standstill" commitment on tariffs,
the European Commission said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin last July assured
President of the European Commission Jacques Santer that there
would not be an increase in tariffs overall, a gesture aimed at
improving Russia's negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
However, Moscow later decided that the tariff-cut plan for 1998
would not be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Other issues affecting Russia's application include
intransparent customs legislation, a range of non-tariff barriers,
poor intellectual property protection, and reluctance to join
WTO's Government Procurement Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
