<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM to Visit Mideast to Help Relaunch Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 10 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine will begin Sunday a visit to three Middle East countries
in an effort to help relaunch the peace process, blocked since the
Israeli conservative government came to power in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine will visit Lebanon, Syria and Jordan, all of them very
close with France, after he visited Israel, the Palestinian
territories and Egypt in December.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio RMC Moyen Orient today, Vedrine said
that although the situation in the Middle East is not good at the
moment, France is "in a position" to help relaunch the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"France feels to be in a position, taking into account the
particularly close relations it has with almost all the
protagonists, to make move the things in a good direction," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that one cannot "live with" the present situation of
relations between Israel and Palestinians and those of Israel with
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
"One should not give up, one should untiringly try to rebuild
the base of the peace process, of searching for a solution,
re-awakening the process which was once engaged, precisely because
the present situation is dangerous," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that contacts have been regularly made between
President Jacques Chirac and U.S. President Bill Clinton, between
himself and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the
situation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We compare our views, they are not exactly the same, but one
should precisely make converge what is common, in any way to
re-awaken the peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that there exist differences between France and
Lebanon over how to implement United Nations Security Council
Resolution 425 adopted 20 years ago after the first invasion of
Lebanon by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The resolution calls on Israel to immediately withdraw its
forces from southern Lebanon it has been occupying.
</P>
<P>
Israel has hinted that it could withdraw from southern Lebanon,
on the condition that Lebanon arrange security measures there as
is required by Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
