<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Agrees to Compensate for Eastern European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The German government has agreed
to compensate for eastern European Holocaust survivors, said a
German press report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper Berliner Tagesspiegal reported that Bonn
would, from 1999 to 2002, provide 50 million marks (28 million
U.S. dollars) per year for a special foundation run by Jewish
organizations to help survivors.
</P>
<P>
The agreement and its details would be officially announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tagesspiegal, Friedrich Bohl, head of
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's office, worked out the concrete terms
last week with Jewish Claims Conference, a New York-based body
founded in 1951 to represent Jewish claimants living outside
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the about 18,000 Holocaust survivors in
eastern Europe, who had so far not yet received any personal
compensation from Germany, would each be paid about 250 marks per
month.
</P>
<P>
However, the recipients should be poor, and should also have
been detained for a certain period in either a concentration camp
or in a ghetto sealed off by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that most Holocaust survivors living in eastern
Europe have never been individually compensated by Bonn as those
in the West. Bonn paid lump-sum compensation to eastern European
nations after the end of the Cold War, but most of the money did
not reach individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Trains More National Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Petroleum
Albina Assis said here today that the country will attach great
importance to training national professionals on the petroleum
front to ensure a sustainable development in the petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks during a meeting with officials from the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Angola's petroleum industry has witnessed
rapid development in the recent years. But the lack of national
professionals has affected the industry's long-term advancement.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has stipulated that foreign oil companies
operating in Angola has the obligation for personnel training
in the profession.
</P>
<P>
Albina revealed that the training of national professionals
has always been a priority in the ministry's objective. In 1997,
a total of 2,683 Angolans were training in foreign companies,
which accounted for 62.7 percent of all Angolans in the industry.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum industry in Angola has made great stride in
recent years, with daily oil output increasing from 600,000
barrels two years ago to the present 750,000 barrels. It is
estimated that by early next century, the output will reach one
million barrels a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
