<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Finds Possible Link Between CJD, Hormone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- A French bodybuilder who died of
new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (nvCJD) might have been
infected by injections of a growth hormone, a French doctor said
today.
</P>
<P>
The patient developed CJD, the human form of mad cow disease,
in 1994 and died two years later, Dr Jacques Verdrager from
Meylan, France, wrote in a research letter to the British journal
Lancet.
</P>
<P>
It is "surprising" that the French bodybuilder contracted the
disease so early in the outbreak of the mad cow disease, Verdrager
said.
</P>
<P>
At that time only one person in the UK had developed nvCJD,
despite the fact that France is one of the biggest importers of
British beef.
</P>
<P>
It is possible, Verdrager said, that the bodybuilder's death
might be a result of the injection of a growth hormone, known in
France as somatotrophine and used to be prescribed for "tissue
repairs."
</P>
<P>
The development of CJD in the patient in 1994 was consistent
with the drug's use in France in the late 1980s, Verdrager said.
</P>
<P>
Somatotrophine, which was popular among French bodybuilders,
has been banned in France since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-10 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Ross's Trip Ends Without Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today said that the
just-concluded trip to the region by U.S. peace envoy Dennis
Ross ended without results.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the reamrks during his telephone conversation
with King Hussein of Jordan, the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center (JMCC) said.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, the two leaders exchanged views on
the latest development in the peace process in light of Ross's
visit to the region, according to the JMCC.
</P>
<P>
Other PNA officials also expressed their dissatisfaction over
Ross's visit. PNA Higher Education Minister Hannan Ashrawi Friday
night said that Ross's visit achieved nothing.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi accused the U.S. administration of siding too much
with Israel, saying that during his four-day shuttle diplomacy
between Israel and the PNA territories starting on Tuesday, Ross
did not do enough to force Israel to honor the signed agreements
with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Marwan Kanafani, spokesman of Arafat, said Friday night that
U.S. President Bill Clinton's scheduled separate talks later this
month in Washington with Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu will be the last chances for bringing the
Middle East peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
The PNA cabinet met Friday night in Ramallah and issued a
statement criticizing the Israeli government for planning to build
more new housing units for Jewish settlers in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel's plan for constructing more new housing units in the
West Bank will push the troubled peace process to a break of
disaster, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli government official said Wednesday that the
government has approved a plan for building nearly 600 new housing
units in Efrat, a Jewish settlement south of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Besides sharp criticism by the PNA toward this plan, even
Ross termed it as an obstacle for bringing the peace process back
on track.
</P>
<P>
"This is the kind of action we've said is not helpful to put
the (peace) process back on track," Ross said on Thursday after
his meeting with Arafat in Ramallah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
