<HEADLINE> Palestinian State Helps Counter Israel: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Ambassador to the
Arab League Mohamed Sobeih said today the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state will deter Israel's hardline
government.
</P>
<P>
"A democratic, secular Palestinian state must be set up on all
the Palestinian land to face up to the Israeli Prime Minister
(Benjamin) Netanyahu's intransigence and insistence on building
and expanding settlements," Sobeih told the Egyptian Middle East
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said that the recent mission by U.S. Mideast peace envoy
Dennis Ross has failed "due to Netanyahu's refusal to budge an
inch on his earlier stances."
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, Netanyahu has announced that he will expand
the settlements, Sobeih said, referring to a decision by Israel to
build more than 600 new homes at two Jewish settlements in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have deadlocked over Israeli
building of a new settlement in East Jerusalem since last March.
</P>
<P>
"The ideal solution to the crisis is to set up a unified
democratic Palestinian state in which the two peoples
(Palestinians and Israelis) would enjoy the same plights and have
the same duties," he said.
</P>
<P>
"After the failure of Ross's mission, the U.S. must defend its
credibility before the entire world, which believes in the peace
process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ross on Thursday criticized the new Israeli decision, a move
that defied U.S. calls for a "time-out" on settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy arrived in the region on Tuesday for talks with
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat to try to pave way for separate meetings they will have
with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington later this month.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih ruled out the possibility that a tripartite meeting
would take place in Washington among Clinton, Arafat and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian presidential envoy will inform Cairo of the
outcome of Ross's recent meetings in Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule city of Ramallah, he added. 
</P>
