<HEADLINE> Sudan-Egypt Ties Augur Well: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Ambassador to Egypt
Ahmed Tayeb Youssef Kordofani today expressed his conviction that
things augur well for the improvement of Cairo-Khartoum ties.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador made the remarks after a meeting with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on the occasion of ending his tour of
duty here.
</P>
<P>
"I am leaving Egypt with the hunch that Egyptian-Sudanese
relations were returning to their normal courses," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador, at the end of his three-year stint in Cairo,
added that bringing back relations to normal has been his aim ever
since he came to Egypt more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Things augur well and it is only natural that the relations
return to normalcy," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the exchange of visits between the two countries' leaders,
he said that these issues are being discussed and at the right
moment, dates of such visits would be announced.
</P>
<P>
In a show of rapprochement with Khartoum accused of harboring
militants to overthrow Cairo's secular government, Egypt has said
recently that it expects the turning of "a new leaf" in its
relations with its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, President Hosni Mubarak's political advisor, on
Tuesday described the Cairo-Khartoum ties as "time-honored and
highly special" and referred to the recent statements by some
Sudanese officials calling for plastering over their differences.
</P>
<P>
Amid signs of improved Cairo-Khartoum ties, Egyptian Trade and
Supply Minister Ahmed Gowaili has invited Sudanese Foreign Trade
Minister Othman al Hadi to visit Egypt in mid-January for talks on
enhancing joint investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, a delegation of the Sudanese Ministry of
Transportation and Communication arrived here for talks on
resuming Nile navigation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On January 3, Sudanese First Vice President el Zubeir Mohammed
Salih confirmed that Egyptian and Sudanese efforts for restoring
bilateral relations are going in full swing and will be crowned by
a visit of President Omar al Bashir to Egypt soon.
</P>
<P>
The present thaw in relations followed assurances from Khartoum
that it will no longer provide support to Islamic militants acting
to undermine the Egyptian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
