<HEADLINE> Pakistan President Shocked over Mominpura killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Rafiq
Tarar has expressed deep grief and shock over the loss of innocent
lives in a terrorist attack Sunday on a religious gathering near
Mominpura, Lahore.
</P>
<P>
The president condemned this dastardly act and hoped that the
government would take all necessary measures "to apprehend the
culprits and award them exemplary punishment."
</P>
<P>
Tarar called for restraint and collective efforts to stem the
menace of sectarian terrorism which, he termed as "a conspiracy
against Pakistan and Islam."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister for Religious and Minorities Affairs
Zafarul Haq has also expressed his deep sense of grief and
resentment on the brute act of violence against the peaceful
citizens in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Sunday, the minister said that it
was not a crime connected with sectarianism but was a pre-planned
act of terrorism related to the regional security situation.
</P>
<P>
At least 24 Shiite Muslims including women and children were
killed and 30 others injured by unidentified gunmen Sunday morning
near Lahore, Pakistan's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
According to initial reports, these people were killed at a
religious gathering at Moninpura graveyard near Lahore when four
unidentified gunmen opened indiscriminate firing at them.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen have managed to escape from the spot and so far no
individual or group has claimed responsibility for the killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
