<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams Makeup of UNSCOM inspection team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today criticized the
makeup of a U.N. weapons inspection team that arrived in Baghdad
Sunday as "not balanced" and "un-evenhanded."
</P>
<P>
An official spokesman told the Iraq News Agency today that the
U.N. team, headed by Scott Ritter, an American accused by Baghdad
as a U.S. spy, is dominated by Americans and Britons.
</P>
<P>
There are nine Americans, five Britons, a Russian and an
Australian on the new team of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
in charge of overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of
mass-destruction.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans, together with the Britons, make up the majority
of the commission and dominate the activities carried out by it
in both New York City and Iraq," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have always raised the question of the imbalance of the
composition of UNSCOM, as well as the activities carried out by
this commission in Iraq," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that so long as this imbalance in the
composition and activities of UNSCOM lasts, Iraq insists its
reservations on the statements and conclusions of the special
commission.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused American arms inspectors of
carrying out instructions of the U.S. Administration instead those
of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
It ordered the expulsion of the American inspectors on November
13. They were allowed to return, together with other inspectors
who then pulled out to protest the eviction, only after Russian
mediation a week later.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. weapons inspectors have accused Baghdad of hiding
information and materials of secretive biological and chemical
weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has been exerting pressure on Iraq to allow it
unrestricted access to sites it deemed suspicious, including
presidential palaces and other what Iraq declared "sensitive
sites."
</P>
<P>
Baghdad insists those presidential sites are "off-limits" to
arms inspectors because they are signs of Iraqi sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The head of UNSCOM Richard Butler is expected in Baghdad
January 19 for a three-day visit to persuade Iraq to open the
sites to weapons inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
