<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance System in Southern China Absorbing Shock of Change (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The auctioning off of the
Guangzhou Special-Shape Steel Plant did not send shock waves
through the workers of Guangzhou, the capital of China's Guangdong
Province, even though some of its workers were certain to lose
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
The plant was sold because of poor management and bad
performance and was mired in debts that had no way of being paid
back. But, why were the workers so undisturbed?
</P>
<P>
One didn't need to look very far for the answer: the workers
all had pension insurance, and unemployed people will receive
social welfare from the local government while they're looking for
a new job.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong province has established social insurance for 6.6
million people from all walks of life, from provincial leaders and
government officials, employees of state-owned enterprises and
institutions to the self-employed.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists say that the insurance has become a kind of shock
absorber in the province and helps it maintain order during the
period of transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, nearly 13 local enterprises in
Guangzhou have been sold or allowed to declare bankruptcy over the
past two years, and nearly 4,500 retirees and 6,000 jobless people
benefited from the insurance.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of people laid off from state-owned
enterprises will continue to grow in the coming years, the
officials say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
