<HEADLINE> Chinese See New Form Of Entertainment In Musical Drama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- On a Chinese stage, a cat named
Leonie finally realizes his dream of becoming a man and sees the
warmth and the coldness, the love and hatred, and the kindness and
wickedness of a small town, and people on the stage are dancing
and singing and asking Leonie to come to live with them.
</P>
<P>
The audience are in a festive mood and join the actors on the
stage in singing the theme song, and after the performance, go to
the stage to offer flowers.
</P>
<P>
This scene took place a couple of days ago at a local Beijing
theater where "The Cat Who Wants to be A Man" was performed by the
Central Academy of Drama's Musical Theater Troupe.
</P>
<P>
The play was written by a Japanese author who based it on the
work of an American playwright.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yinzi, who manages public relations for the troupe, says
that musical drama is a mixture of dance, song, and dialog that has
been performed in western countries for decades but is new to
Chinese. But, even though musicals are somewhat unfamiliar,
audiences are becoming more familiar with them. She says the
troupe will perform the American musical "West Side Story" soon.
</P>
<P>
A few years ago, the academy opened a musical drama section to
train musical actors and the troupe was recently set up by using
the first music drama grads. The main purpose of the troupe is to
keep these first graduates useful, Zhang says.
</P>
<P>
Some local experts say that musicals in fact are quite similar
to various Chinese operas, although dancing is rare in a Chinese
opera or is quite different from European-style or American-style
dance routines.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese artists are trying to introduce musicals to
China. Wang Gang and Cheng Fangyuan, a husband and wife team of
well-known artists, are preparing a musical based on the Oscar
winning "Song of Music", and say they are confident Chinese
audiences will like musicals in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture's China Culture and Arts Corp. also
plans to invite a number of foreign musical theater troupes to
perform in China this year, and some local artists are even
predicting that 1998 will be the Year of the Musical for China's
stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
