<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance System in Southern China Absorbing Shock of Change (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the computer screens of the Guangzhou Municipal Social
Insurance Administration Bureau, pension accounts can be seen,
opened by people from top provincial officials to the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
The administration bureau is the province's only administrator
of government-supported social insurance services. And every
social insurance service has experienced a trial period before
being put into full operation.
</P>
<P>
However, in many other Chinese provinces, people working in
non-state economic sectors have not taken part in the local social
insurance system.
</P>
<P>
Besides social insurance, about 7.3 million people in Guangdong
have been insured against industrial injury; 4.6 million people,
against unemployment risks; and 1.8 million female workers, insured
against child-bearing risks.
</P>
<P>
Medical insurance, aimed at reforming the former medi-care
system set up under the planned economy, has also been in trial
operation with 350,000 insured.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Guangdong had accumulated a total of 6.8 billion
yuan in social insurance funds, and the balance of social
insurance funds increased to eight billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong had as many laid-off workers from the state economic
sectors as other provinces at the beginning of the 1980s, when the
country was tuning to a market economic reform.
</P>
<P>
"Guangdong Province has woven a 'safety net' with social
insurance to support its economic growth, while keeping a stable
public order," local officials point out.
</P>
<P>
That is why most reform policies taken by the local government
did not arouse anxieties among local people, they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
