<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Sends Sympathy For Chinese Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto has extended his sympathy to the victims of Saturday's
earthquake in northern China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
"I offer my most heartfelt sympathy concerning reports that
numerous lifes have been lost and great damage has been caused by
the earthquake," Hashimoto said in a telegram to Chinese Premier
Li Peng Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Foreign Minister keizo Obuchi also sent a
similar telegram to his Chinese counterpart Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring 6.2 on the Richter scale, struck Shangyi
and Zhangbei counties in the Hebei province, 220 kilometers
northwest of Beijing, at 11:50 local time Saturday. At least 47
people were killed and 11,439 were injured. Some 800 homes in
Shangyi county were damaged or collapsed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
