<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1400 GMT, January 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Sunday that
agreement on the outline of a political settlement in Northern
Ireland is "quite close".
</P>
<P>
"I am still cautious, but optimistic, we can get a proper
settlement in Northern Ireland because I believe there is so much
agreement and so much goodwill there," Blair told the BBC's
Breakfast program.
</P>
<P>
The peace process could be moved on "very quickly" after May,
if the critical breakthrough was made, he added. (UK-PM-N.Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- A man was shot dead by gunmen in a car at a club in
Belfast, capital of Northern Ireland, early on Sunday, BBC
reported.
</P>
<P>
The victim was one of several doormen who were standing outside
the club.
</P>
<P>
The taxi was later found burnt out in the east of the
city. Police said they have not yet established a motive for the
attack.(UK-Killing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Bulgaria and Russia still have differences on the
supply of Russian natural gas to Bulgaria, Kiril Gegov, deputy
chief of the Bulgarian Energy Committee, said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, Gegov, who had just returned from Moscow after a
three-day visit, said both sides agreed to continue working on the
transit rates of Russian gas through Bulgaria because there are
also differences in their proposed methods for calculation.
(Bulgaria-Russia-Differences)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam's National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh
Saturday told his visiting Iraqi counterpart that Vietnam supports
Iraq's aspiration to be free from an eight-year U.N. embargo.
</P>
<P>
Manh made the remarks during his talks with the visiting Iraqi
National Assembly Speaker Saadun Hammadi who began a week-long
visit to Vietnam Saturday. (Vietnam-Iraq-Ties) 
</P>
</TEXT>
