<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister Warns Over Price Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of
Information, Posts and Telecommunications Chen Chimutengwende has
warned that the government could soon impose price controls on
basic commodities to curb the price hikes.
</P>
<P>
This follows recent unrealistic increases in the prices of
goods and services amid allegations that some white businessmen
were bent on causing problems to ordinary people by hiking prices
of basic goods.
</P>
<P>
The minister was reacting to reports that some businessmen had
hatched a plot to hike the prices to unrealistic levels so that
the lives of the ordinary people would become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
"The government is aware of the plot by some white
businessmen. I would like to warn them that they will not succeed
in making the lives of the masses unbearable. If they carry on
with their ploys we might be forced to control the prices again,"
Chimutengwende said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had agreed to some of the conditions
imposed by the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
which stipulated that prices of goods and services must be
determined by market forces.
</P>
<P>
"If we control the prices we will be in a difficult situation
with the IMF and the World Bank. Western donor countries will
also not want to deal with us. They will boycott us for following
such policies," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
However, some sections of the business community were taking
advantage of the situation by coordinating their efforts to
ensure that the prices are pushed to unrealistic levels so that
the government could be blamed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government was aware that some whites
were bitter about the land redistribution exercise and were
trying to use every possible means to discredit the government.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to assure them that they will not win. The land
distribution process is part of the liberation process. I have to
reach its logical conclusion. If the government does not take the
land, then the people will," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
