<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Summer Resort Still Active in Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Even after the 2.2
million summer tourists left the 200 sanatoriums and 300 hotels of
Beidaihe, a famous summer resort in northern China, the place was
not in a state of hibernation.
</P>
<P>
The winter's first snow turned the 70 square kilometers Beidaihe
Peninsula into a crystalline world, but Beidaihe still has ample
sunshine, a gentle sea breeze, and evergreen trees.
</P>
<P>
Tourists may have left, but birds and other animals enjoy the
natural scenery of Beidaihe. Because it's in the flight path of
migratory birds, it has bird sanctuaries that play host to 405
species of birds, a third of the country's total number. There are
also peacocks, elephants, and lions in the local zoo.
</P>
<P>
Winter is a busy planting season here. About 500 trees are
being added to a 10,000-m. green corridor, which now has 320,000
trees, and a green coverage rate of 63 percent.
</P>
<P>
The director of the regional tourism bureau says that 1998 is
Beidaihe's 100th anniversary as a summer resort. It was set up
during the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), and a series of activities
will be held this year.
</P>
<P>
A move is now underway to build Beidaihe into a conference
center, and recovery center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
