<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cleaning Up One of China's Most Polluted Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Water quality in the Huaihe
River, one of China's most seriously polluted, has improved after
three years of treatment by the local government.
</P>
<P>
Water quality in the main stream is now stable, according to
Wei Fusheng, member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, and is
clearly better than in 1994. A recent sample of the water showed
it at the level of Class Three Ground Water, meaning it can be
used as a drinking water source.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the country listed the Huaihe as one of the key big
rivers and lakes that need help, and the State Environmental
Protection Agency began monitoring the main polluters along the
river in 1997, and monitored the entire river valley seven times.
</P>
<P>
Local government regulations meant the closing down of 50
enterprises that did not stop discharging pollutants into the
river.
</P>
<P>
Although pollution in the main stream is under control, Wei
says, the problem is that the branches still have various levels
of pollution, and the goal of cleaning the Huaihe up by the year
2000 will require considerable effort on the part of the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
