<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Warns Against Failure of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian spokesman
warned today the failure of the talks to be hosted by U.S.
President Bill Clinton with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and PNA leader Yasser Arafat could restart Palestinian
violence.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Tayeb
Abdel Rahim was quoted by Israel Radio as saying that if the
Washington talks fail, the Palestinian people would renew their
popular struggle.
</P>
<P>
Rahim reiterated that the PNA regarded the just-concluded
visit to the region by U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross as a
failure. He called the Washington talks as a "moment of truth" in
breaking the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to meet with Netanyahu on January 20 and
with Arafat on January 22 in a bid to push forward the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. The PNA is expecting Clinton
to increase his pressure on Israel to carry out the long-delayed
second phase troop pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Due to inner bickering over the scope of the pullback,
Netanyahu announced last week that his government would divide
the pullback decision into two parts, one on the scope and
another on the implementation. He conditioned the implementation
on the PNA's fulfillment of commitments to the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
This move was termed as an attempt to further delay the
redeployment in order to avoid hardliners within Israel's
splintered coalition from toppling the government.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day shuttle mission between Israel and the
PNA, Ross tried but failed to narrow the wide gap between the two
sides over the scope of pullback. Israel is reportedly only
willing to redeploy troops from eight percent of the West Bank,
while the PNA demands for about 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
