<HEADLINE> IMF Envoy Meets With Indonesian Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A special envoy of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) met with officials of the
Indonesian Monetary Council here Sunday, but no result of their
discussions on economic reforms pledged under an IMF-led
multibillion-dollar bailout package for Indonesia was announced.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's first deputy managing director Stanley Fisher, who
arrived here Saturday morning, had discussions with some ministers
of the Indonesian government at 2 p.m. local time at the building
of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Fisher said after the three-hour meeting that their
discussions were successful till now but it will take more times
to have further negotiations in depth.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting just starts," he said. The meeting will also be
joined by IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus who is expected
to arrive here next Thursday, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad, who walked out of
the building after having discussions with the IMF envoy, said,
"the discussions were constructive and satisfied."
</P>
<P>
Other ministers did not make any comments on their discussions
with Stanley Fisher.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono, who also attended the
meeting, said the IMF envoy will meet President Soeharto, but he
did not say when and where the meeting will take place.
</P>
<P>
The IMF envoy's visit was triggered by the sudden fall of the
Indonesian rupiah (national currency), which declined to a record
low of 11,000 per dollar last Thursday, promoting U.S. President
Bill Clinton to telephone President Soeharto on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also decided to send Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers to Indonesia to discuss the economic situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the IMF along with the World
Bank and the Asian Development Bank agreed to provide 23 billion
US dollars financial and technical assistance to Indonesia to
overcome its monetary crisis and Indonesia committed to conduct
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the reports said the IMF has expressed its
dissatisfaction over the process of Indonesia's economic reforms
in the two months.  
</P>
