<HEADLINE> Iraq Unsatisfied With Composition of New UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today expressed serious
reservations at any statements and findings that a new team of
U.N. arms inspectors are likely to release, the Iraqi News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad's announcement followed the arrival of a 16-member
team of U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction in Iraq on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The new team is led by American Scott Ritter, called by Iraq
"father of trouble makers," with eight other Americans, five
Britons, one Australian and one Russian as members.
</P>
<P>
An official Iraqi spokesman was quoted by the news agency as
saying that Iraq has repeatedly raised the question of unbalanced
composition of UNSCOM teams on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He noted that U.S. and British nationals constitute the majority
of the team, making it easy for them to steer the commission work.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait
seven years ago can only be lifted when the UNSCOM says the
country is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
But the UNSCOM teams have complained of troubles in cooperation
with Iraq, while Baghdad accuses the U.S. and Britain for blocking
the lifting of the sanctions. 
</P>
