<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seismologists Predict More Quake Activity For Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Seismologists at China's State
Seismology Bureau (SSB) have analyzed data from yesterday's
earthquake and say there is a possibility of aftershocks measuring
about five on the Richter Scale in Zhangjiakou Prefecture in Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiakou was hit by an earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter
Scale near noon on Saturday. The area hit, around Zhangbei and
Shangyi in the northern part of Hebei, has been included in an SSB
danger zone, which covers the northwestern part of Beijing and the
juncture of Shanxi and Hebei provinces and the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Before yesterday the coal mining city of Datong in Shanxi had
been hit by two quakes measuring more than six on the Richter
Scale.
</P>
<P>
Gao Xu, deputy director of the Beijing Seismology Bureau, says
there is a good possibility of quakes measuring four or five on
the Richter Scale occurring in the danger zone in the near future,
and explains that earthquake activity parameters in the zone
recently are abnormal, with more frequent and more intense
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
China is frequently hit by earthquakes and has had four active
periods this century, and a period from the late 1980s to early
next century is a fifth. From 1988 to 1996, there were six
earthquakes measuring above seven on the Richter Scale on the
mainland and offshore areas, and scientists say that earthquakes
measuring seven or even higher are possible during this period.
</P>
<P>
Seismological predictions have long been a questionable
topic. It is difficult for seismologists to make accurate
predictions about most earthquakes, and they mainly calculate
earthquake conditions in a certain area during a certain period of
time to reduce the amount of losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
