<HEADLINE> Iranian Speaker Slams Algerian Government for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Majlis (parliament)
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri today slammed the Algerian
government for recent massacres of hundreds of Algerian people,
saying the massacre was a plot against Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio quoted Nouri as saying at an open session of the
Majlis that it was the Algerian government that armed a group of
people to massacre Muslims, but the Algerian government said
that Muslim radicals were responsible for the killings of hundreds
of Muslims.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Algerian government and the West had a direct
hand in the massacres of Algerian Muslims in recent weeks,
"because they could not endure the growing trend of Islamic
movement in the country."
</P>
<P>
During the past two weeks, over 400 Algerians have been
reportedly killed by unidentified armed groups. The massacres
caused great concern all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Nouri expressed regret to the "indifference of Islamic
countries and international community toward the massacres in
Algeria."
</P>
<P>
He also attacked the international human rights bodies for
their "silence" over the massacres.
</P>
<P>
"They (the human rights bodies) accused Iran of violating the
rights of Iranian women, who actually play an active role in the
country, but they did not talk about the issue of human rights
when they saw hundreds of women and children were tortured and
slain in Algerian," Nouri argued.
</P>
<P>
He called on the world Muslims to "learn a lesson from the
multi-standard policies and lies of the West," saying that
Muslims should remain cautious when they are developing ties with
the West.
</P>
<P>
Following the reports about Algerian massacres, Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi contacted with foreign ministers of
Italy, Syria, Morocco and Greece during the past several days,
expressed Iran's deep concern over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also sent letters to secretaries general of the
United Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference,
calling for immediate measures to end the bloody killings of
Algerian people. 
</P>
