<HEADLINE> Japanese Donates Money For Chinese Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Takami Kunio, who lived
through the Osaka-Kobe earthquake, donated 60,000 Japanese yen
today to the Earthquake Headquarters of Zhangbei County in Hebei
Province, northern China.
</P>
<P>
The county was hit at 11:50 am (Beijing Time) Saturday by an
earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale, which caused many
casualties and heavy property damage.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Kunio is the director of an Osaka organization and has been
involved in afforestation work in China's Shanxi Province in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
When the quake hit, he was working with local tree-planters in
Shanxi's Tianzhen County, he said, and felt the tremor and learned
about the quake on the evening TV news. So, he drove to Zhangbei this
morning and was the first foreigner to make a donation for relief
funds, 10,000 yen of which came out of his own pocket, and the
rest from his organization
</P>
<P>
"The quake has indeed caused enormous damage to the area," he
told Xinhua, "but I'm deeply impressed by the efficient rescue
activities here."
</P>
<P>
While Mr. Kunio was visiting the area, army helicopters
airlifted 25,000 kg of bread to the victims, and soldiers were
busy clearing away the rubble of damaged houses and setting up
tents for the homeless. More relief is on its way from other parts
of the country, officials say. 
</P>
