<HEADLINE> Chiluba Promises not to Seek Third Terms of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has promised not to seek a third term of office and urged
party members to look for someone else to succeed him, Sunday
Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Saturday at the renewal of his party membership in
Lusaka, Chiluba, also leader of the ruling Movement for
Multi-party Democracy (MMD), reiterated his wish to accept the
terms of the republic constitution, saying others should take
over because the constitution allows a president to rule for two
terms only.
</P>
<P>
"When my term of office comes to an end, don't even think of
retaining me," said Chiluba, who came into power in 1991 and was
re-elected in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said there is speculation that Chiluba is
trying to secure a third term of office.
</P>
<P>
There would be no democracy and good governance without the
respect of law, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba urged all Zambians to understand and appreciate the
rule of law, failure to which they would find themselves in
trouble. 
</P>
