SHANGHAI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Hongqiao
International Airport has become China's first joint-stock
airport following the recent founding of the Shanghai Hongqiao
Airport Joint Stock Co. Limited.
</P>
<P>
The new firm is expected to be listed on Shanghai Stock
Exchange in the near future, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The move will upgrade the airport, and Shanghai will be the
country's only city with two international airports once the new
facility is completed in the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
The municipality is also working to restructure its airport
administrative system.
</P>
<P>
A municipal airport administrative committee, scheduled for
formation in the near future, will consist of officials from
related government departments and airports.
</P>
<P>
Hongqiao Airport was transformed into an independent economic
entity in December 1987, with the result that its transport volume
has since increased by over 15 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The airport has established air links with 97 domestic and
overseas airports, with 42 local and foreign airlines operating
over 300 routes.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the facility handled 13.27 million passengers and
476,000 tons of cargo, thereby by exceeding its designed capacity.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Municipality is striving to attain its goal of
becoming an international economic, financial and shipping
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
