<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Sunday that agreement on the outline of a political
settlement in Northern Ireland is "quite close".
</P>
<P>
"I am still cautious, but optimistic, we can get a proper
settlement in Northern Ireland because I believe there is so much
agreement and so much goodwill there," Blair told the BBC's
Breakfast program.
</P>
<P>
"We need co-operation North-South and some form of devolution
in Northern Ireland for proper government there," he said.
</P>
<P>
The peace process could be moved on "very quickly" after May,
if the critical breakthrough was made, he added
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on Norther Ireland in Belfast began in September
last year and are supposed to end in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
But their prospects have been clouded by increased violence
over the past three weeks, including several sectarian
killings. These incidents have cast doubt on the cease-fires
declared by the main nationalist and pro-British guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
Early on Sunday, just before BBC's interview with Blair, a man
was killed when gunmen opened fire on staff at the entrance to a
nightclub in Belfast. 
