<HEADLINE> Central Government Concerned About Snowstorm-hit Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGQU (Tibet), January 11 (Xinhua) -- On Saturday, an 11-member
government team arrived in a part of Tibet that was hit by
snowstorms to gather information about the extent of the disaster,
people's conditions, and to help with relief work.
</P>
<P>
Since September, some 40 heavy snowfalls have hit Nagqu,
blanketing the plains with 40 cm of snow and mountainous areas
with twice that amount.
</P>
<P>
Herdsmen from Nyainrong County, in the northern part of Nagqu,
holding national flags, met the team members from the State
Economic and Trade Commission, the Civil Affairs, the Health, and
Communications ministries, and the military, shouted "long live
the Communist Party" in the nearly 30 degree Centigrade below zero
weather.
</P>
<P>
"Who would ever have cared about our suffering in the old
days," asked Cewang Doje, the man holding a national flag, "It's
the Communist Party of China that makes us feel the warmth. The
government cares, and we love our socialist country."
</P>
<P>
The central government has allocated 10 million yuan (1.2
million US dollars) in relief fund for Tibet, said Zhang Zhigang,
Vice-minister of the State Economic and Trade Commission and head
of the group.
</P>
<P>
Another six million yuan will be used to re-open roads leading
to the disaster-affected area and four million yuan will be used
for agricultural relief. In Amdo County, near Nyainrong, Yang
Hengyin, Vice-minister of Civil Affairs, handed over relief funds
to local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
