<HEADLINE> Guangdong Ties Hong Kong in Interport Tourney's 1st Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Hong Kong showed how its
soccer team had imporved under the guidance of newly-hired Brazilian
coach when the local team tied with South China's Guangdong Provincial
team 1-1 in the first leg of the two-leg Guangdong-Hong Kong Cup
interport soccer tournament here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The tie laid a sound basis for Hong Kong to reverse the tide as the
local team had lost the last four consecutive tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is now scheduled to meet Guangdong at this weekend in
Guangzhou for the second leg of the home-and-away tournament. The
team with more points from the two games wins the annual tournament.
</P>
<P>
The two goals inthe Sunday match were scored by Hong Kong's Dale
Tempest at the 32nd minute and by Guangdong's Li Zhaoyang at the 51st
minute respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong had surprisingly switched from its usual European play to
a short-passing game featuring a South American style on Sunday to
press the visiting side, especially in the first half.
</P>
<P>
The opening goal came at the 32nd minute at a goal-mouth melee.
Hong Kong's forward Anthony Foster headed a cross from a teammate but
it was blocked by Guangdong's national team goalkeeper Ou Chuliang.
Foster's teammate Dale Tempest dashed up to catch the rebound and
headed it into the goal.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong failed to equalize the score until six minutes into the
second hald, when its midfielder Li Zhaoyang found the net with a slam
shot inside the penalty zone.
</P>
<P>
Both sides failed to convert several other chances to goals in the
rest of the match.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to change, in so short a period of time, the usual
style of play of the Hong Kong players. But you can see the progress
today," said a happy but calm Sebastiao Pereira Araujo, the new Hong
Kong coach from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"I think both sides had failed to turn many chances into goals," he
said. "At least we had waisted two such chances," he admitted.
</P>
<P>
He was optimistic of the coming second-leg match six days away. "I
think our players could do their job better in the Guangzhou match,
before which we have at least four days for training," he predicted.
"They could feel less pressure on themselves in Guangzhou than playing
here on the home turf," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong had won 14 out of the 19 previous tournaments while
Hong Kong took only five, with the last Hong Kong victory coming
in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
