<HEADLINE> Zambia's Former President Formally Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former President
Kenneth Kaunda, who is under house arrest, has been formally
charged with conspiracy against the government, Sunday Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's defense lawyers, according to the paper, confirmed
that Kaunda was charged with conspiring with the army and two
other opposition leaders -- Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC)
leader Dean Mung'omba and Rodger Chongwe, leader of Liberal
Progressive Front (LPF), to topple the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said that the grounds served for Kaunda's
detention indicated that Kaunda, Chongwe and Mung'omba allegedly
agreed to sponsor last October's abortive military coup.
</P>
<P>
The grounds, said the lawyers, allege that the trio pumped in
an undisclosed amount of money for the operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the grounds, the tree opposition leaders entered
into an agreement with the army to sponsor the coup and "it was
agreed that the army would run the country for three months
before finally handing over (power) to Kaunda," said Sacika
Sitwala, one of Kaunda's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers, however, could not give further details on
Kuanda's grounds of detention, insisting that they are still
studying the document. They said that "whatever they throw at us
will not discourage us."
</P>
<P>
Kuanda, who insisted that he is "innocent" and has never
resorted to violence, was detained last December and later
shifted to house arrest for alleged involvement into the military
coup.
</P>
<P>
Chongwe is reported in Australia and Mung'omba has been under
detention for more than 70 days. Over 90 coup suspects have been
arrested without charge under the country's current state of
emergency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
