<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Rising Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's major
economic powerhouse, recorded a foreign trade volume of 58.7
billion US dollars in 1997, up 11 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city's exports surged by 23 percent to 33.5 billion US
dollars, and its imports came to 25.2 billion dollars, matching
the 1996 level.
</P>
<P>
Some 14,100 Shanghai companies have been granted the authority
to handle foreign trade, with state-owned companies once again
emerging as the city's major exporters. State-owned enterprises
accounted for 60 percent of local exports during 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports handled by state-owned companies rose by 19
percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of hi-tech products and products with a high added
value such as computers and integrated circuits, recorded
substantial rises and accounted for 9.6 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The city has tried to improve customs services in a bid to
further increase local foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
