<HEADLINE> Three-Nation Summit Likely to Form Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The coming three south Asian
nation business summit is expected to create a mechanism to "pull
resources together" for the region to unitedly face global
challenges and tap economic opportunities, Bangladeshi government
officials and business leaders said.
</P>
<P>
A task force, comprising businessmen and civil servants from
Bangladesh, India and Pakistan, is likely to be launched by the
conference to carry forward the agenda, with plans for frequent
meetings among the three countries, the officials and leaders were
quoted as saying by local press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The business summit, to be attended by the prime ministers of
the three countries, is scheduled to be held here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We need to emerge as a bloc to negotiate in the global
market," said Yussuf Abdullah Harun, president of the Federation
of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we get together and pull our resources together, we
cannot face the enormous challenges from the West," he said,
portraying the key plank behind the January 15 event.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh businessmen also hoped the business summit to
continue as an annual event, which they proposed to be hosted by
the three capitals by rotation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"How to face the rest of the world in terms of protecting our
interests in areas we have advantages" would be a key question,
Foreign Secretary Mustafizur Rahman added.
</P>
<P>
"We will devise ways how to cooperate and what areas to
cooperate," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
