<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Promises Security in South Lebanon After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has agreed to deploy
its army in south Lebanon to impose order and stability there if
Israel accepts U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 demanding
Israeli troops' withdrawal from there.
</P>
<P>
A Lebanese official relayed this message through Americans to
Israeli Labor Party Knesset (Parliament) member Yossi Beilin
Friday, the English paper the Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report only identified the official as at "very senior"
level and did not give details of the Lebanon-Israel contact.
</P>
<P>
"If the Israelis implement U.N. Resolution 425, as Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai says, then Lebanon will fulfill its
part of the equation which means creating order in south Lebanon,"
the Lebanese official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese move came in apparent response to the offer by
Mordechai last week to withdraw from the security zone provided
Israel's northern security is guaranteed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 with the aim to protect its northern areas
from cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas. Beirut has
called on Israel to withdraw unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, dating back to 1978, calls for an Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon, the restoration of peace and
security and the extension of Lebanese authority over the region.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, founder of the Movement for a Peaceful Departure from
south Lebanon, has said the deployment of the Lebanese army into
areas vacated by the Israeli Defense Forces would be done with the
aid of the U.N peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials believe that Lebanon is intended to end the
guerrilla war against the Israeli occupation in the region and
resume its sovereignty over south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Beilin and other members of his movement are to meet with
senior officers of the U.N. forces in Lebanon, including Commander
of the International Peace-keeping Force Maj.-Gen. J. Konrote in
Jerusalem Wednesday to discuss this matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
