<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authenticity of Returned Thai Artifact Doubted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Some Thai archaeologists have
doubted the authenticity of a piece of artifact returned to
Thailand by a Chicago museum 10 years ago, according to a
front-page report of the Nation newspaper on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Associate Prof. Srisakara Wellibhodama, senior archaeologist at
Silpakorn University, said several archaeologists have been
debating privately whether the returned artifact was the real
lintel stolen from a gate of an 800-year-old Khmer-style temple in
Buri Ram, northeast Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said the likelihood of the returned artifact being genuine
is only 60-70 percent, adding that this kind of artifact can be
replicated easily.
</P>
<P>
Thepmontri Limpaphayom, also an archaeologist, said there is a
possibility that the returned carved article is a fake, because no
scientific tests have been make to verify its authenticity in
terms of chemical composition and age.
</P>
<P>
The returned lintel has been placed back in the original place
in the temple.
</P>
<P>
When the stone carving arrived back in Thailand after a bitter
12-year wrangle between Thailand and the American museum, Thai
fine arts department experts declared it to be the lost valuable
lintel, without making any laboratory tests on its material.
</P>
<P>
The Art Institute of Chicago returned the artifact only after
it was offered a work of art of comparative artistic value to
replace it.
</P>
<P>
Thepmontri have found several marked differences after
comparing old pictures of the lintel and the returned carving.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the genuine lintel was supposed to be carved from
sandstone, but we see a lot of pock-marks on the surface of the
returned lintel."
</P>
<P>
He added that although he was not saying that those are the
proof that the returned lintel is a fake, but it did raise doubts.
</P>
<P>
Thepmontri said he knew a counterfeiter in Ayutthaya, central
Thailand, who claimed to have made a replica of the genuine lintel
after it was stolen from the temple and kept it in Ayutthaya for
some time before being sold to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The counterfeiter made a replica using the real thing as model
by working with half-baked clay, the archaeologist said.
</P>
<P>
A scientist at the fine arts department said, on condition of
anonymity, that the department declared the returned artifact
genuine after comparing it with a sample of carved sandstone which
was used to border the lintel before the theft.
</P>
<P>
She said specialists at her department looked at them with a
microscope and found that the texture, line of cutting, moss and
crafting techniques of the two pieces were consistent.
</P>
<P>
Thepmontri urged the department to call in experts from other
agencies of the government to help verify the authenticity of any
artifacts whose origin and age are in doubt.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the truth about the lintel will emerge in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
