<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Attracts More Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Despite the plunge in
contractual foreign investment nationwide last year, overseas
funds flowing into Tibet increased remarkably.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November 1997, there were 86 foreign-funded
projects in Tibet, mainly in the manufacturing, processing and
tourism industries. Contractual investment in those projects added
up to 62.5 million US dollars, and actual input totaled 25 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Investors were mainly from Nepal, Japan, the United States, the
Republic of Korea and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Seven foreign-funded projects, involving a total contractual
investment of 16.74 million US dollars, were inked in 1997, a
foreign trade official of the Tibet Autonomous Region was quoted
as saying by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The seven projects were in the fields of processing, tourism
and forestry, said Bha Dra, deputy director of the department of
foreign economic relations and trade of Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Bha Dra said Tibet will step up efforts to overcome its
disadvantageous natural conditions and catch up with the economic
growth in other areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
As the geographical and natural conditions in Tibet are not as
good as those in other parts of the country, the central
government has granted Tibet a privilege -- an enterprise
registered in Tibet can locate an office or plant in any part of
the country, on condition that the enterprise pays tax to the
Tibet regional government, Bha Dra said.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan economy has gone through amazing changes over the
past four decades. However, it is largely dependent on supplies
and support from other parts of the country and cannot stand on
its own feet.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is very important for the region to speed up the
development of its own industries, " Bha Dra was quoted as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
