<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- The ice storm that ravaged central Canada in the past
five days eased off Saturday, with freezing rain stopped and sun
shining again in some areas.
</P>
<P>
In the capital region, power was gradually restored to
thousands of customers who had been without electricity for the
past four days. Yet, about 10,000 homes in the capital were still
blacked out. Tens of thousands more had no power in surrounding
areas, local reports said. (Canada-Ice Storm)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZHANGBEI, CHINA -- Forty-seven people have died and over 9,000
people have suffered injuries, including 1,246 people with serious
injuries, in the earthquake on Saturday which struck Shangyi and
Zhangbei counties in Zhangjiakou Prefecture, north China's Hebei
Province, lastest statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale hit the area,
located some 220 kilometers northwest of Beijing, the Chinese
capital, at 11:50 a.m. local time (0350 GMT). The direct economic
losses are preliminarily estimated at least one billion yuan
(about 120 million U.S. dollars). (China-Quake-Toll-Updated)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- British ambassador Sir Andrew Wood said here Saturday
that Britain firmly opposed paying the ransom in exchange for the
two Britons who have been held as hostage in Chechen since
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
Wood made the remarks in an interview with a Russian radio
station, "Moscow Echo." He said, up to now, Britain had no
information about the two hostages. "We know they are still alive,
but they have not contacted with us." The two Britons, who were
involved in humanitarian aid in Chechen, were kidnaped by local
militia. The kidnappers have not put forward conditions for
releasing the hostages. (Russia-Hostages) 
</P>
</TEXT>
