<HEADLINE> Israel on High Alert Against Terror Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A large number of Israeli
security forces were deployed in public places today amid
intelligence warnings about terrorist attacks by Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
Roadblocks were set up at the entrances to major cities,
causing serious traffic jam. Armed soldiers and policemen
patrolled shopping areas and central bus stations, which are easy
targets for terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
Police Inspector General Yehuda Wilk called on the public to be
vigilant against any suspicious people and objects and inform the
police immediately.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Friday night told Israeli
television Channel 2 that Israeli security forces had received
information that Islamic extremists plan to stage an attack in a
major city, but no specific location had been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said he had asked U.S. peace coordinator Dennis
Ross, who ended his four-day mediation mission in the region
Friday, to urge Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to do everything
possible to prevent the attack.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported today that Israeli soldiers had arrested
five members of the anti-Israeli Islamic militant group Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) near the West Bank city of Ramallah.
They were suspected of attempting to launch an attack in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has been launching suicide bombing attacks in crowded
buses and public areas in Israel and it is responsible for the
latest two suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem in late July and
early September last year.
</P>
<P>
The bombings in the Mahane Yehuda vegetable market and Ben
Yehuda pedestrian mall killed 25 people and wounded hundreds of
others, dealing serious blows to the stalled Israeli-Palestinian
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
