<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC Forging Closer Ties With IFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) is trying to forge closer ties
with its long-time rival, the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP), the
Sunday Independent newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the ANC eyes a coalition government in
Kwazulu-Natal soon and a merger of the two parties in the longer
term.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal, where the IFP is based, is the only province
governed by the IFP.
</P>
<P>
ANC heavyweights, including former president Nelson Mandela,
President Thabo Mbeki, Deputy President Jacob Zuma, are
propelling the drive, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted ANC insiders as saying that a merger or
coalition proposal had been circulated at a special provincial
working committee meeting of the ANC's Kwazulu-Natal region this
week. In the proposal the ANC outlines the run-up to a possible
merger of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The proposal suggests that the ANC offer IFP leader,
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, a national position befitting his stature,
most likely the deputy presidency under Thabo Mbeki after the
1999 general election. It also suggests creating an ANC-IFP
coalition in the province after 1999.
</P>
<P>
The proposal suggests that either Buthelezi dissolve the IFP
and bring his followers into the ANC, or the two parties continue
to exist separately but share a single election list.
</P>
<P>
However, Dumisane Makhaye, an ANC spokesman in Kwazulu-Natal,
denied that the special provincial working committee had
discussed a merger proposal.
</P>
<P>
But Makhaye said a summit between the national and provincial
leaders of the two parties was being planned.
</P>
<P>
The summit, to take place very soon, would discuss closer
cooperation between the parties, and would be led by Mbeki and
Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
However, ANC secretary-general, Kgalema Motlanthe, said it was
premature to talk of a merger between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
"A merger between the ANC and the IFP is a very serious issue
and should be clarified with the ANC's alliance partners, the
SACP (South African Communist Party) and Cosatu (Congress of
South African Trade Unions) first. As far as I know this has not
happened," he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar views have been expressed by the IFP side as well as
the SACP and Cosatu.
</P>
<P>
Mandela asked for a merger between his party and the IFP, the
biggest black opposition, on the eve of ANC's 50th national
conference held in Mafikeng, North-West province in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
The idea was opposed by white-based opposition parties, which
feared that a merger would give the already powerful ANC too much
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
