<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Buy 27 Multi-Purpose Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran has decided to buy 27 new
multi-purpose cargo, container and passenger ships worth 700-800
million U.S. dollars, local English-language daily Tehran Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Iran's Shipping Company Ahmad Mohammadi
told local press Saturday that the new ships would replace 44
aging oceangoing ships in Iran with more than 20 years of
service.
</P>
<P>
He said that his company has signed contracts with South
Korea and China and would sign new contracts with some other
countries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will build six 22,000-ton multi-purpose ships for
Iran and the first one will be delivered to Iran in June,
Mohammadi said, adding that his company has also issued license
for purchase of four 73,000-ton cargo ships valued at 32 million
dollars each from South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, five more 22,000-ton multi-purpose ships
would be purchased from China with the first one being delivered
in January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
So far Iran owns 110 ships, 76 of which are oceangoing,
Mohammadi said. He noted that his company should get
international certificates for its another 21 oceangoing ships by
July, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Split 25km Open Water Swim Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian Alexi Akatiev on Sunday
became the first double gold medalist at the World Swimming
Championships as he added the 25km open water title to his 5km top
honor lifted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Akatiev, from Moscow, clocked five hours five
minutes and 42.1 seconds, beating Spaniard Davic Meca by less than
two minutes.
</P>
<P>
After chasing 1997 European champion Akatiev in the last five
kilometers, Meca slowed down in the final stages while the Russian
sprinted through the breakwater to reach the finish first.
</P>
<P>
Meca, hailing from Barcelona, clocked 5:07.22.9.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Chaillou won Argentina's first medal here when he timed
5:07.52.6 for the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
"It was a very hard race with very difficult waves. I'm very
tired but very happy and thrilled to have two gold medals,"
Akatiev said.
</P>
<P>
Chaillou said that a bronze medal was just what he aimed for.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I could finish between about third and eighth place but
it wasn't until the end of the race when I saw the breakwater that
I knew the bronze medal was mine," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 25km race, American Tobie Smith timed 5:31.20.1
to win the gold medal. She was followed by Germany's Peggy Busche
and the Netherlands' Edith van Dijk, at 5:32:19.2 and 5:38:06.9
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Buchse was in the top three from the start and made a charge
toward the lead at around the 8.5km mark. Then for some time she
swapped the lead with Italian Valeria Casprini.
</P>
<P>
After the halfway mark Smith started moving ahead from fourth
place and locked the second spot at about the 13.5km mark.
</P>
<P>
In the dying stages the American surged to the lead and got to
the finish about 100 meters ahead of Buchse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
