<HEADLINE> More Relief goods Rushed to North China Earthquake Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGBEI (Hebei), January 11 (Xinhua) -- Batches of disaster
relief materials from Beijing and the People's Liberation Army
have been sent to the quake hit areas in north China in succession
today.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhangjiakou Prefectural Government, by 11:00
today, 2.14 million yuan worth of goods and funds have arrived at
the quake-hit areas or on their way here.
</P>
<P>
The disaster relief materials include 1,200 tents, 21,085
cotton overcoats and quilts as well as 15,000 kilograms of food
and an amount of medicine.
</P>
<P>
At 10:00 this morning, the armed forces stationed in Beijing
airlifted 15,000 kilograms of food to Zhangbei and Shangyi
counties.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven people have died and 11,439 people suffered
injuries, including 1,252 people with serious injuries, in the
earthquake on Saturday which struck Shangyi and Zhangbei counties
in Zhangjiakou Prefecture, north China's Hebei Province, according
to latest statistics released by Zhangjiakou Anti-Quake and
Disaster Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters said more than 44,000 people have become
homeless as 13,606 houses have collapsed in Zhangbei, Shangyi and
neighboring Wanquan County, and another 26,000 houses were cracked
and deemed dangerous to enter.
</P>
<P>
The direct economic losses are estimated at 2.39 billion yuan
(288 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale hit the area,
located some 220 kilometers northwest of Beijing, the Chinese
capital, at 11:50 a.m. (Beijing Time) yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
