<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ban on Kenya's Fish Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan government official
has criticized the European Commission for its decision to ban
fresh fish import from four African countries including Kenya,
the Sunday Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper quoted James Mwanza, Director of Medical
Service, as saying Saturday that the decision taken by the
commission because of the concerns over cholera was "unfortunate
and harsh".
</P>
<P>
The ban which takes immediate effect was approved by the
commission's veterinary panel which met in Brussels Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official noted that although parts of the country
had lately been facing sporadic cholera outbreaks due to the
unusually heavy rains, Kenyan health authorities had taken
measures to contain the spreading of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza said he was surprised that the commission arrived at
this "punitive decision" despite being adequately informed on the
measures being implemented by the Kenyan government.
</P>
<P>
Other African countries which have been affected by the ban
are Tanzania, Uganda and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The East African region has been suffering since last November
from unprecedented heavy rains due to the El-Nino weather
phenomenon resulting in an upsurge of water-borne diseases,
especially cholera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
