<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Between Manila, Rebels Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Sunday hailed the agreement reached by his government and the
National Democratic Front (NDF) on the human rights issue, saying
it is "a major turn in our country's quest for a just and lasting
peace."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Ramos admitted that a final peace
accord with the NDF is still "a long way off."
</P>
<P>
But he said the agreement reached Saturday by the two sides in
their talks in the Hague, the Netherlands, shows "no obstacle is
insurmountable to brother Filipinos really committed to the ways
of peace and unity."
</P>
<P>
Ramos encouraged both sides to "seize the current momentum
toward a peace settlement as a gift to our people who have praying
for peace and deserving to have it in their country."
</P>
<P>
In a joint press statement issued from the Netherlands,
government and NDF representatives said that they initialed the
draft of the first three parts of the agreement and exchanged
drafts on the provision of International Humanitarian Law Saturday
after six days of talks.
</P>
<P>
"Both panels believe that the agreement reached on the
provisions on human rights is a big step forward in our common
quest for a just and lasting peace and lays a solid foundation for
its attainment," they said in the statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
