<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gujral to Lead High Level Economic Team to Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 11 (Xinhua)-- Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral will lead a high level economic team to Dhaka to take part
in the trilateral summit of Bangladesh, India and Pakistan
beginning from January 15.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the Ministry of External Affairs has listed
three major factors coalescing in the upcoming summit. First, all
three countries are in the process of economic restructuring and
are looking for a convergence of economic policies. Secondly,
there is a greater realization that the creation of a "larger
economic space" is an imperative of regional cooperation. In other
parts of the world, the trend is towards larger economic groupings
to benefit from synergy; the feeling here is that South Asia
should not get left behind. Thirdly, since all three countries are
open to foreign direct investment, foreign investors would find a
combined South Asian market comprising more than a billion people
more attractive.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, there will be three working sessions: on
ways to improve trade; on improving infrastructure, particularly
transportation; and on joint ventures including energy.
</P>
<P>
Gujral will have a bilateral meeting with Bangladesh Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina on the eve of the summit and will have a
bilateral meeting with Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif after
the summit, the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
