<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Quantity of Rubber Sheets Ruined in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Over 20 million u.s. dollars'
worth of para rubber sheets stored in a warehouse in south
Thailand were destroyed in a devastating fire, which had lasted
more than 30 hours.
</P>
<P>
The blaze near Hat Yai, the largest city in south Thailand, was
still raging late Saturday night after it broke out at about 3 PM
Friday afternoon, according to the Bangkok Post on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The fire followed an order two weeks ago by Deputy Minister of
Agriculture and Cooperatives Somchai Sunthornwat to check the
quantity of the para rubber sheets stored in the warehouse for
export to China.
</P>
<P>
Official documents show that a total of 44,000 tons of rubber
sheets, purchased by the previous administration in a price
intervention scheme to help rubber growers, were kept in the
rented warehouse.
</P>
<P>
However, several local businessmen who are involved in the
rubber business said they doubted the amount of rubber sheets in
storage matches the official figure, and suspected arson to cover
up suspected irregularity.
</P>
<P>
The raging fire and foul smell had prevented police and local
officials from entering the warehouse to determined the cause of
the blaze.
</P>
<P>
When Somchai inspected the warehouse, he already noticed that
the sheets were not stored in proper order and remarked that
should a fire break out, it would cause extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local health and rescue officials have been put on
alert in case the emissions pose a hazard to the people living in
close proximity to the warehouse, which is only about 10
kilometers from Hat Yai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Wins US Figure Skating Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Michelle Kwan performed a
flawless routine to win her second title in three years at the
United States Figure Skating Championships in Philadelphia on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kwan thus took the crown from the 15-year-old Tara Lipinski who
dethroned Kwan as US and world champion last year.
</P>
<P>
Kwan received the ever highest scores at a US final with eight
perfect 6.0s and a 5.9 for artistic merit plus eight 5.9s and a
5.8 for technical merit.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski rose from fourth after a fall in her short program to
second overall.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski and third-placed Nicole Bobek were also awarded
Olympic berths, meaning all the three women will make their
Olympic debut next month in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Kwan, who has been recovering from a stress fracture in her
left toe, said, "It was the performance of my life right now. I'm
ready for the Olympics. Let's go." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
