<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for Cooperation in ASEAN Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Sunday called on members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) to cooperate in tapping potentials of tourism in
order to overcome the region's currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Opening the ASEAN Tourism Forum in the Southern Philippine City
of Cebu, Ramos said that the meeting is being held "at a time when
we and other countries in Asia are experiencing a severe currency
crisis."
</P>
<P>
"Your presence tells me that you have every confidence tourism
will substantially help overcome Asia's present crisis and return
to the path of economic recovery and eventually vigorous growth,"
Ramos told representatives of ASEAN member countries at the
meeting, which will end on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that tourism in Asia will continue to grow even if, in
the short term, there will be a serious slowdown for some
economies due to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If ASEAN were to get even a 10 percent share of the world
travel and tourism market, this could mean the injection of 38
billion U.S. dollars into the economy of the region," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
He said that one positive results of the present crisis is that
the ASEAN leaders have begun to work much more closely with each
other in order to arrive at a solution.
</P>
<P>
"In the process of finding a solution to the currency turmoil,"
he said, "the realization has grown that we are indeed
inter-dependent in ASEAN and that it is in our best interest to
further expand and strengthen our economic investment, trading and
tourism linkages."
</P>
<P>
The tourism forum is lined up with activities that will
showcase the best that the region has to offer in the field of
travel and tourism. The Most important of these is the ASEAN
Travel Exchange, a tourism marketing activity geared towards
opening opportunities for the suppliers of ASEAN travel products
and services.
</P>
<P>
Tourism revenue has accounted for 8 percent of the region's
gross national product in the past few years. But the industry has
suffered a big setback since the currency crisis hit the region
last July. ASEAN governments are encouraging their people to stay
at home to save foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
Last year's forest fire in Indonesia also affected the
environment in the region and scared away would-be tourists from
other parts of the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
