<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimmers Urged to Do Best in Perth Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese swimmers will do
their best in the championships starting on Monday despite one has
been suspended for violation of the delegation rules, a Chinese
official said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Shi Tianshu, head of the Chinese swimming delegation, told
Xinhua that the Chinese swimmers were going to swim their best in
the championships which run from January 12 to 18.
</P>
<P>
"Even though our training here has been interrupted by media
interviews and drug testing, we will put up the best swims as we
can and go for gold medals," he said.
</P>
<P>
World record holders Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan are favored for
women's medley titles. Chen will also vie for a gold medal at the
200 meters freestyle, the event in which she is ranked No.1 in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Shan Ying, world No.1 in the women's 50 meters freestyle, will
have a shot at a sprint title.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation leader dismissed local media reports
that the Chinese swimmers had a plan to use drugs in Perth as
"sheer fabrication".
</P>
<P>
"You should not regard an individual case as a collective
action," Shi said.
</P>
<P>
"And you can't say that someone must have used a banned drug
because he or she brought it to a friend here," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmer Yuan Yuan was found having a drug in her
baggage in the Sydney Customs' routine checks on Thursday. A
laboratory in Sydney said the drug was human growth hormone, which
is used to cure children's slow growth but banned in the sports
world.
</P>
<P>
Yuan's coach Zhou Zhewen on Saturday told a hearing by the
International Swimming Federation's doping panel that he put the
drug into Yuan's bag in Beijing and it was a friend in Australia
who asked him to bring it over here.
</P>
<P>
Both Yuan and Zhou have been suspended from the Perth Worlds by
the Chinese delegation, which has a rule that no delegation member
is allowed to bring anything to anyone in outside China. The two
now face more severe penalty from the Chinese Swimming Association
(CSA).
</P>
<P>
Shi, CSA vice chairman, reiterated the Chinese swimming
governing body's stand against doping.
</P>
<P>
"We has the anti-doping policy -- clear stipulation, strict
testing and severe punishment," he said. "We have never wavered in
the fight against doping, and will never."
</P>
<P>
China had conducted 3,540 drug tests on its sportmen and women
in the year of 1997, with over 650 tests, incluing 460 flight
tests, taken against swimmers.
</P>
<P>
In November and December last year, the world swimming body
FINA had conducted 104 drug checks on Chinese swimmers.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Yuan alone had taken eight tests within these two months,
according to CSA secretary general Yuan Jiawei.
</P>
<P>
"The numbers of tests and the fact none of the Chinese swimmers
tested turned out positive show CSA's determination and results in
the battle against the performance-enhancing drugs," Shi said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation leader noted that doping was an international
problem.
</P>
<P>
"Last year swimmers in other countries had been caught using
banned drugs. That means doping is an international problem and
the fight against it is an arduous task," Shi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
