<HEADLINE> Textile Industry Faces Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- China's debt-laden textile
industry, focus of the nationwide drive to restructure state-owned
enterprises, has no choice but to resolve its difficulties within
three years with aid of preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
The policies include that export rebates for textile products
will increase to 11 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi Wanpeng, president of the China National
Textile Council (CNTC) said that
</P>
<P>
The CNTC will eliminate 10 million spindles and lay off 1.2
million workers in three years. In 1998 alone, 4.8 million
spindles will be scrapped and 600,000 workers be laid off.
</P>
<P>
An oversupplied market plus the burden of mammoth welfare
payments for employees and retired workers have pushed the state
sector into slump.
</P>
<P>
The industry's deficit increased to 10.6 billion yuan (1.28
billion US dollars) from 1.9 billion yuan over the period of
1993-1996. Over 40 percent of the companies are on the brink of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for us to use all resources available to pull the
industry out of its slump," the CNTC president said, according to
today's China Daily.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nagano Olympics Sell 80 Percent of Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- With 26 days to go before the
Nagano Winter Olympics, more than 80 percent of the tickets have
been sold, organizers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, There are 257,000 tickets still available, including
500 for the opening ceremony slated on February 7 and 150 for the
men's ice hockey finals which will go on sale on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the winter Olympics history, the 1994 Lillehammer games
recorded the best ticket sales, with about 87 percent of the
tickets sold, said Norihiko Iijima, spokesman for the Nagano
committee.
</P>
<P>
Nagano organizers have already reached the target of 5.3
billion yen (40.3 million U.S. dollars) in ticket sales for their
budget.
</P>
<P>
Ticket prices range from 2,000 yen (15 dollars) for some events
to 35,000 yen (270 dollars) for the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Still available are 33,000 tickets for Alpine skiing, 6,100
tickets for the closing ceremony and 50 tickets for the women's
figure-skating free-program competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
