<HEADLINE> Shares Lose Ground on BSE market Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 11 (Xinhua)-- Share prices lost ground on
the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market as the foreign funds
refrained from fresh allocations in the new year resulting in the
sensitive index shedding about 190 points last week.
</P>
<P>
The continued turmoil in Asian markets and the Moody's decision
to put India on the "watch list" also helped the downward
movement.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index moved up initially to 3739.21, but
later fell back sharply breaking two support levels to end the
week at 3530.20 as against previous weekend close of 3719.85,
netting a fall of 189.65 points. The national index shaded 80.79
points to close the week at 1533.49 from previous weekend close of
1614.28. The BSE-200 and U.S. dollar index were quoted down at
343.59 and 144.06 at the weekend compared with previous weekend
close of 361.58 and 153.34 respectively.  
</P>
