<HEADLINE> Ice Storm Eases Off in Central Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The ice storm that ravaged
central Canada in the past five days eased off Saturday, with
freezing rain stopped and sun shining again in some areas.
</P>
<P>
In the capital region, power was gradually restored to
thousands of customers who had been without electricity for the
past four days.
</P>
<P>
Yet, about 10,000 homes in the capital were still blacked
out. Tens of thousands more had no power in surrounding areas,
local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien toured the capital region
Saturday, as well as the hardest-hit province of Quebec.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that he will not leave Sunday with the Team
Canada trade mission to Mexico, Brazil, Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Governor General of Canada Romeo LeBlanc will go instead,
Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
In Montreal, power returned to some of the downtown areas. More
than three million people in and around the city remained without
power.
</P>
<P>
Troops have been called into the eastern Ontario and Quebec
provinces to help out with the relief effort.
</P>
<P>
So far, the worst storm in almost 40 years has caused 11 deaths
due to the freezing temperature and carbon monoxide poisoning from
gas stoves.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency in Ottawa and dozens of surrounding
cities continues in effect Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
