<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan President Calls for National Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- President Arnoldo Aleman
presented his first government report Saturday, in which he called
on his fellow countrymen to "actively and jointly take part in the
construction of a Nicaragua for all."
</P>
<P>
Aleman, who assumed his mandate one year ago, read his speech
before Parliament amidst a disorder raised by deputies from the
opposition Sandinista Front for National Liberation (FSLN), who
made a protest against policies of the liberal government.
</P>
<P>
Aleman's report covered domestic and foreign, social, economic
policy, and policies for the construction of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
During the first year of Aleman's administration, Nicaragua's
inflation rate dropped from 12 percent in 1996 to 7 percent in
1997. Meanwhile, the gross domestic product was up 5 percent, the
highest in Central America, Aleman said in the report.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country's exports surpassed 750 million
U.S. dollars in 1997 for the first time in the past 20 years,
contributing to the creation of more jobs especially in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
After acknowledging that "the road we have ahead is long and
difficult," Aleman promised that in 1998 his government "will give
special attention and preference to the neediest social sectors in
the rural and urban areas."
</P>
<P>
"In economy, there are no miracles," Aleman said, adding that
only work, savings, investment and discipline will help surmount
the challenges that Nicaragua has to face in the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
