<HEADLINE> Economic Briefs From Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs in
the Southern Common Markets (Mercosur) countries.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil registered a 714 million dollar trade
deficit with its three Southern Common Market (Mercosur) partners
during the first 11 months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
In that period, Brazil imported from Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay goods and services worth 8.966 billion dollars, while
exporting 8.252 billion dollars to the three countries.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina had a record output of motor vehicles
in 1997 with 445,869 units, 42.4 percent more than in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay has applied since January 1 for a three
percent increase to the customs tariff it levies on imports from
countries out of Mercosur, in compliance with a decision of the
Southern Common Market approved on December 15 in Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Two gas deposits were discovered recently in a
zone some 80 kilometers (50 miles) north of the Gallegos River in
the province of Santa Cruza.
</P>
<P>
The oil company which made the exploration said that one of the
wells can produce 650,000 cubic meters of gas per day, and 30
cubic meters of condensed gas at a depth of 2,830 meters.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian motor vehicle manufacturing
industry produced last year a record figure of 2.077 million
vehicles, up 14.5 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Association of Motor Vehicle Manufacturers
announced that 1.86 million vehicles were sold in the country and
the rest exported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
