<HEADLINE> Britain Opposes Paying Ransom For Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 10 (Xinhua) -- British ambassador Sir Andrew
Wood said here Saturday that Britain firmly opposed paying the
ransom in exchange for the two Britons who have been held as
hostage in Chechen since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
Wood made the remarks in an interview with a Russian radio
station, "Moscow Echo." He said up to now, Britain had no
information about the two hostages. "we know they are still alive,
but they have not contacted with us."
</P>
<P>
He said Britain would not encourage the action of taking
hostages by paying the ransom. He believed that the two hostages
would eventually be set free.
</P>
<P>
The two Britons, who were involved in humanitarian aid in
Chechen, were kidnapped by local militia. The kidnappers have not
put forward conditions for releasing the hostages. 
</P>
