<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Price Index Enjoys Lowest Annual Rise in Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's price index in 1997
rose by 3.6 percent over 1996, the lowest in a decade, the Vietnam
News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said the reason behind the low rise is the sharp
drop in the prices of starchy food which is the largest commodity
group.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the figures of 1996, the price index of starchy
food dropped by 3.7 percent while the prices of industrial and
non-food commodities rose by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The price index is currently rising at a stable 0.6 percent to
1.8 percent, the report said. 
</P>
