<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Decides to Review or Postpone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
announced here Saturday night that it was shelving seven
megaprojects and put another eight under review, for the second
time in five months.
</P>
<P>
The decision was contained in a decree signed by President
Soeharto Saturday, Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
The 15 projects -- eight power projects, four toll road
projects, one airport projects, one building project and one
equipment-provision project -- were among dozens originally
shelved or reviewed in September last year in a bid to save
billions of dollars of badly needed foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
Moerdion said the government had earlier planned to continue
the megaprojects but a review of each of them had shown they would
be too costly and lessen the government's capability to deal with
the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The projects were reviewed November 1 last year according to a
presidential decree. When news of their resurrection came, there
were allegations of nepotism because they were projects tied to
politically well-connected business groups, local newspaper "The
Jakarta Post" said.
</P>
<P>
The sudden resurrection of the projects also raise doubts about
the government's commitment and ability to seen through tough
economic reforms, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Reports said, International Monetary Fund (IMF) First Deputy
Management Director Stanley Fisher and U.S. Deputy Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers are due here on Sunday to discuss
economic reforms pledged under an IMF-led multibillion-dollar
bailout package to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The visit are triggered by the sudden fall of the Indonesia
rupiah, which declined to a historic low of 11,000 against the
U.S. dollar on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 200 percent of its value against
the greenback since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in his discussion with Soeharto by telephone on
Friday, underscored the importance of Indonesia's commitment to an
IMF-led bailout package in exchange for some 40 billion U.S.
dollars in standby loans.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team plans to assess developments and to negotiate an
acceleration of the reform program. IMF Managing Director Michael
Camdessus is scheduled to arrive here on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
