<DOCNO> XIE19980111.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Economist Dismisses Fears of Development Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Brisk development and stable
domestic consumption are anticipated in 1998, and will suffice to
fuel China's economic engine this year, said a chief economist
with the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, SSB chief economist, dismissed concerns about a
major slowdown in China's economic growth and speculation that the
country might devalue its currency to maintain the contribute of
exports to economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Today's Business Weekly of China Daily quoted Qiu as saying
that "we do not need to do that. It will not be difficult for
China to achieve growth of around 8 percent under current
conditions."
</P>
<P>
China's gross domestic product increased by 8.8 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The daily noted that observers worrying about China's economic
growth momentum said the country would run into difficulties in
maintaining increases in investment, consumption and exports --
the three major forces driving economic growth.
</P>
<P>
As domestic production capacity for most products exceeds
demand, Chinese companies are generally not active in launching
new industrial projects, they said. The banks have also become
very cautious in granting new loans, which may limit industrial
growth.
</P>
<P>
Qiu emphasized, "but there is still a huge amount of room for
investment, " adding that technological renovation, high and
new-tech projects, infrastructure and farmland water conservancy
projects can all be major targets for new investment.
</P>
<P>
The SSB's chief economist believed that investment activities
will play the same or even a bigger role in propelling the economy
forward.
</P>
<P>
He said the current oversupply situation in many goods does not
indicate that the country's consumption will experience either a
standstill or decline.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people's current average living standards mean more
room for consumption growth.
</P>
<P>
The economist forecast demand for consumer goods in 1998 would
rise by 10 percent, compared to 10.7 percent for 1997.
</P>
<P>
He believed that investment and consumption may contribute a
greater share of economic growth in 1998 than they did last year
as China's exports are predicted to fall, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Qiu stressed that a high growth rate is no longer the prime
target for China, it has been replaced by improvements in
industrial structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
