<HEADLINE> Seriously Injured People in Quake-Hit Areas Receive Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZNAHGBEI (Hebei) January 11 -- More than 1,200 seriously
injured people in the quake-hit Shangyi and Zhangbei counties in
Zhangjiakou Prefecture, north China's Hebei Province, have
received preliminary medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven people have died and over 2,000 people suffered
injuries, including 1,246 people seriously, in the strong
earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter scale at 11:50
a. m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Its epicenter was located about 220 kilometers northwest of
Beijing. More than 70,000 houses were collapsed in the quake.
</P>
<P>
Local hospitals and those of the of People's Liberation Army
stationed at the province have sent 12 medical teams to the two
counties to rescue wounded people.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua learned at 5 a.m. this morning that the first batch of
disaster relief supplies from Beijing is expected to arrive here
soon.
</P>
<P>
The supplies, including 10,000 overcoats and quilts, together
with tents, medicine and food and 1 million yuan (120,000
U.S. dollars) of disaster relief fund were collected urgently by
the municipal government last night.
</P>
<P>
The temperature there last night was about 20 degrees
centigrade below zero and quite a number of homeless people have
installed tents along the highways.
</P>
<P>
A provincial rescue team headed by top provincial officials
arrived at the quake-hit areas hours after the quake, and the
State Seismological Bureau sent a team to the areas one hour and a
half after the quake, to help organize rescue work and monitor
after-quakes.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,500 soldiers from the Beijing Military Command left
for the quake hit areas four hours after the quake and have sent
there 500 tents and 5,000 overcoats.
</P>
<P>
When Xinhua reporters made interviews at Xiahe Village in
Zhangbei County at around zero hour last night, a group of
soldiers were distributing overcoats to homeless farmers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, dozens of old people, kids and wounded people
were staying in a passenger bus of the military rescue team while
soldiers were rescuing properties for farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
