<HEADLINE> Mongolian PM Says GDP Grows by 3.3 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's gross domestic
product in 1997 was up 3.3 percent, Prime Minister Mendsaikhan
Enkhsaikhan said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Animal husbandry is Mongolia's most important agricultural
sector. Enkhsaikhan quoted a recent report of the National
Statistics as saying that in 1997 the country boasted a record
output of 31.3 million livestock animals.
</P>
<P>
The output of crops was up 10 percent from the previous year,
which was also the first growth the country has ever registered
since 1990, Enkhsaikhan said.
</P>
<P>
As for the industrial output, he said it increased by 4.3
percent at constant prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inflation rate plummeted from more than 50
percent in 1996 to 17.5 percent in 1997, which helped create
favorable conditions for the country's efforts in maintaining
stable exchange rates and attracting more investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also promised continued reforms in order to promote a more
rapid economic growth in 1998. 
</P>
