<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The global economy is outgrowing the earth's
ecosystem and it needs to be restructured for a new development
model, the Washington-based Worldwatch Institute said in a report
issued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"If the world economy as it is now structured continues to
expand, it will eventually destroy its natural support systems and
decline," said Lester Brown, president of the institute, at a
press conference here.
</P>
<P>
In a 250-page report, the State of the World 1998, the
institute said the key environment indicators are increasingly
negative while all the global economic indicators are positive.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- In spite of the crisis on the Asian markets, the
economic outlook in Europe continues to inspire confidence,
according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The economic sentiment indicator fell from 103.5 to 103.0, but
this is mainly attributed to a decline in stock prices, European
Report, a twice-weekly newsletter published here Saturday, quoted
an economic survey by the European Union (EU)'s executive body,
the European Commission, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The industrial confidence indicator for Europe remained at the
same high level in November as in October though stock markets
reported a decline in all EU member states between the two months.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A hostage crisis which occurred in Tajikistan this
morning was settled in the capital Dushanbe Saturday evening, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Five Tajik government officials, including a deputy mayor of
Dushanbe, captured by supporters of field commander Rakhmon
Sanginov's opposition faction Saturday morning have been released
without any conditions, according to Tajik Deputy Prime Minister
Abdurakhmon Azimov.
</P>
<P>
A group of Sanginov's faction took the five officials as
hostage in the morning, demanding the release of three members of
the group detained by police on January 7 for illegal possession
of arms.
</P>
<P>
The report said a principal agreement on the unconditional
release of the hostages was reached at an urgent meeting of the
National Reconciliation Commission Saturday, which was attended by
the commission's chairman, leader of the United Tajik Opposition
Sid Abdullo Nuri and field commanders.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A Russian governmental delegation and the Chechen
government held a two-hour talk in Grozny Saturday on how to
restore the economy of the breakaway republic, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by Deputy Prime Minister Ramazan
Abdulatipov, arrived in Grozny on Saturday morning. "We come to
Chechnya to start a normal, creative work," he said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Forty-seven people have died and over 2,000 people
have suffered injuries, including 250 people with serious
injuries, in the earthquake which struck Saturday in Shangyi and
Zhangbei counties in Zhangjiakou Prefecture, north China's Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale hit the area,
located some 220 kilometers northwest of Beijing, the Chinese
capital, at 11:50 a.m. (Beijing Time).
</P>
<P>
The tremors were felt by people living over a large area,
including Baotou and Hohhot in the west, Qinghuangdao and Tianjin
to the east, and Shijiazhuang and Taiyuan to the south.
</P>
<P>
Three aftershocks measuring measuring 4.6, 4.5 and 4.2 on the
Richter Scale were recorded after 18:00 p.m. (Beijing Time),
according to the latest report from the State Seismological Bureau
(SSB).
</P>
<P>
The SSB reports that over 70,000 houses in 13 townships
covering some 1,000 sq km, have either collapsed or sustained
heavy damage, with more than 60,000 structures located in Zhangbei
County, also the county in which 47 people died.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Four Palestinian youths were wounded in a severe
clash with Israeli soldiers in the West Bank city of Hebron
Saturday, the Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) said.
</P>
<P>
The clash between some 100 Palestinian youths and Israeli
soldiers occurred at an Israeli checkpoint near the Shuhada
Street, which was closed to traffic long time ago following the
clashes between the Palestinians and Jewish settlers in the city.
</P>
<P>
The four injured were sent to the Alia Hospital for
treatment. The Palestinians also threw a Molotov cocktail at the
Israeli police Patrol, the JMCC added. 
</P>
