<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major Beijing-based newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- An earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale hit north
China yesterday, according to the State Bureau of Seismology
sources.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter center was located 41.1 degrees north latitude
and 114.3 degrees east longitude in Shangyi County northwest of
Zhangjiakou, in Hebei Province, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, who is also General Secretary of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) central committee, and Premier Li
Peng called provincial leaders in Hebei province yesterday
afternoon, expressing deep concern over the earthquake occurred in
two counties in Zhangjiakou Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Li asked provincial leaders to convey their
solicitude to the relatives of those who died as a result of the
quake and people in affected areas.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that local officials and ordinary
people will work hard, unite as one, reduce losses brought about
by the quake to the minimum, and restore production and
development, and rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
"China Youth Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Forty-seven people have died and over 2,000 people have
suffered injuries, including 250 people seriously, in the
earthquake which yesterday struck Shangyi and Zhangbei counties in
Zhangjiakou Prefecture, Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismological Bureau reports that over 70,000 houses
in 13 townships covering some 1,000 sq km, have either collapsed
or sustained heavy damage.
</P>
<P>
The SSB has ruled out the possibility of aftershocks measuring
above 6.2 on the Richter Scale in the area of the epicenter, and
predicts that ensuing aftershocks will measure less that 5.0 on
the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
 "Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing Municipal Government took emergency measures to
collect 10,000 pieces of cotton-padded clothes and quilts over the
night for people in Zhangjiakou Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
A team has left for the disaster area with relief materials
which include medicine, food, tents and one million yuan in cash
(over 120,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
 "Business Weekly" (China Daily)
</P>
<P>
-- Brisk investment and stable domestic consumption are
anticipated in 1998, and will suffice to fuel China's economic
engine this year, said a senior official with the State Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist of the Bureau, dismissed concerns
about a major slowdown in China's economic growth and speculation
that the country might devalue its currency to maintain the
contribution of exports to economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
