<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Parliament Deplores Disorder Caused by FSLN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The new Nicaraguan National
Assembly directive board, not recognized by the National
Liberation Sandinista Front (FSLN), deplored on Saturday the
incident occurred in the parliament by the protest of the
Sandinista caucus.
</P>
<P>
President Arnoldo Aleman delivered his first annual
governmental report to the National Assembly Saturday morning, but
the Sandinista deputies banged on the tables and shouted slogans
against him.
</P>
<P>
The FSLN protested the "illegal" election of the directive
board of the parliament held Friday, in which the Sandinista
caucus did not have the two posts it wanted.
</P>
<P>
The directive board charges the Sandinista deputies, in a
communique, of lack of respect to the place and to the fatherland
symbols, the constitution and the national flag.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of this power of the state, we apologize to the
diplomatic corps, to the representatives of the other powers of
the state, and special guests, for this deplorable incident that
we expect will be overcome with the maturity, the high-level civic
discussion, and the patriotism for the good of the Nicaraguan
harmony," says the communique.
</P>
<P>
It adds that the president delivered his speech "despite of the
disorder lamentably introduced by FSLN deputies and people who do
not belong in the Parliament."
</P>
<P>
At the end of the session, the head of the Sandinista caucus,
Victor Hugo Tinoco, announced new protests in the Parliament and
in the streets until a new election of the National Assembly
directive board is held.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly directive board added in the communique
that "it informs the Nicaraguan people that it has already started
the normal activities corresponding to the 14th Legislative
Period, and that it will continue promoting laws of national
benefit and for the modernization of the Parliament." 
</P>
</TEXT>
