<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutchman Sets To Win European Speedskating Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, Jaunary 11 (Xinhua) -- Rintje Ritsma of the
Netherlands underlined his chance to win the championship when he
took another gold in the men's 1,500-meter at the European
Speedskating Championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ritsma stormed home in 1:54.22, adding his second gold medal to
Friday's 5,000-meter event where he clocked 6:57.10 and finished
first. He was also the silver medalist in the men's 500-meter
event in 37.85 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Cedric Kuentz and Russian Vadim Sayutin followed
Ritsma in the 1,500-meter to win the silver and bronze in 1:54.46
and 1:55.85 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ritsma's win boosted his hope to win the championship with an
overall points of 117.633 to top the standings after three events.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 1,500-meter, Claudia Pechstein of Germany scored
her straight win and grabbed the gold in 2:04.64 after she
finished first in Friday's 500-meter event in 41.61 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Russian Svetlana Bazhanova finished second in 2:05.69 and
Pechstein's compatriot Anni Friesinger finished third in 2:05.80.
</P>
<P>
Friesinger staged a comeback in the women's 3,000-meter and win
the gold in 4:19.99. Bazhanova and Pechstein clocked 4:22.76 and
4:23.27 respectively to take the silver and bronze.
</P>
<P>
Both Pechstein and Friesinger justified Germany's dominace at
the Championships, topping the three-event overall standings with
127.034 and 128.694 points respectively despite their defending
champion compatriot Tonny de Loor placed eighth with a meager
point of 131.424.
</P>
<P>
Three Dutchmen and three German women will join in the last 12
skaters to compete in the men's 10,000 and women's 5,000-meter
events on Sunday, which will decide the European speedskating
champion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
