<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke - Colombia Sets Targets for Anti-Drug Operation in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Colombian police
announced a plan Saturday for their anti-drug operation in 1998
which included the eradication of 40,000 hectares of coca and
opium poppy plantations, and the seizure of 40 tons of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Anti-drug Police Director Leonardo Gallego said they also
planned to confiscate 150 tons of marijuana and 6,000 tons of
chemicals and capture 1,500 drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Gallego said that the burning of confiscated drugs and the
eradication of illegal cultivations will be done in jungle and
mountain areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Colombia has more than 60,000 hectares of
land cultivated with coca plants, opium poppy and marijuana.
</P>
<P>
In their similar operation last year, Colombian police
destroyed 48,151 hectares of illicit cultivations, confiscated 41
tons of cocaine, dismantled 115 drug-processing laboratories, and
closed 58 clandestine landing strips.
</P>
<P>
Also, they detained 1,519 Colombians and 71 foreigners
suspected of being involved in drug trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
