<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Colombia to Reexamine Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Colombian Foreign Minister
Maria Emma Mejia will make a three-day visit to Venezuela on
Februry 20 to promote the border demarcation in the Perija
mountain range.
</P>
<P>
Mejia will meet her counterpart Miguel Angel Burelli Rivas to
stress the importance of starting works of demarcation in the
Perija mountain range, to prevent future incidents due to lack of
knowledge of the limits of each country.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers arrived at this consensus after surmounting
the last border incident in 1997, in which Venezuelan military
trespassed by mistake into Colombian territory and captured three
Colombian citizens who later were returned to their country, with
the corresponding explanations to the Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
The need of defining limits in the mountain range was
stated by the two diplomatic chiefs in reciprocal communiques last
December.
</P>
<P>
The zone of Perija is one of the most difficult point of 30
other pending matters in the process of demarcation of the 2,219
kilometer border shared by the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
