<HEADLINE> Worldwatch Warns Global Economy Outgrow Ecosystem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The global economy is
outgrowing the earth's ecosystem and it needs to be restructured
for a new development model, the Washington-based Worldwatch
Institute said in a report issued today.
</P>
<P>
"If the world economy as it is now structured continues to
expand, it will eventually destroy its natural support systems and
decline," said Lester Brown, president of the institute, at a
press conference here.
</P>
<P>
In a 250-page report, the State of the World 1998, the
institute said the key environment indicators are increasingly
negative while all the global economic indicators are positive.
</P>
<P>
Between 1950 and 1997, the global economy expanded from an
annual output of 5 trillion U.S. dollars to 29 trillion U.S.
dollars, an increase of nearly six-fold.
</P>
<P>
Growth during the seven years since 1990 exceeds that during
the 10,000 years from the beginning of agriculture until 1950,
according to the report, which was published annually since 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
With the speedy economic growth, consumption of natural
resources has also increased unprecedentedly in the last half
century with the use of wood more than doubled, that of paper
nearly six fold, fish consumption increased five-fold and water
use tripled.
</P>
<P>
"The economy continues to expand, but the ecosystem on which it
depends does not, leading to an increasingly stressed relationship
between the two," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The signs of stress can be seen in shrinking forests, falling
water tables, eroding soils, disappearing wetlands, collapsing
fisheries, deteriorating rangelands, rivers running dry, rising
temperature.
</P>
<P>
"These environmental indicators make it clear that the Western
fossil fuel-based, automobile-centered economy is not a viable
model for the world," said Brown.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that nowhere are "the ultimate limits of
the Western economic model more visible than in China."
</P>
<P>
"Because China is growing at such an extraordinary rate, it is
in effect telescoping history," said Brown.
</P>
<P>
"China is teaching us that the Western industrial development
model will not work for China because there are not enough land,
water, and energy resources for everyone in China to consume at
U.S. levels," he added.
</P>
<P>
The report underlined the urgency of restructuring the
economies, not just of China and other developing countries, but
also of the industrial world.
</P>
<P>
"Recognizing the limits of natural system is often attacked as
a call for no growth... the issue is what kind of growth, and
where," Brown added.
</P>
<P>
The report demonstrated that the human kind already have the
technologies to meet the challenge of building an economy that is
ecologically sustainable.
</P>
<P>
"A sustainable economy is one that reuses and recycles
materials, is powered by renewable energy sources, and that has a
stable population," a press release by the institute said.
</P>
<P>
"Stabilizing population as soon as possible -- and well before
it reaches 9.4 billion -- is the first step to building a
sustainable economy," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Flavin, one of the authors of the State of the
World, noted, "Just as challenge is unprecedented, so too are the
economic opportunities for the countries and companies that
pioneer the technologies needed to get us there."
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the global wind power business, already valued at
2 billion U.S. dollars annually and expanding at 25 percent per
year, as one of several new growth sectors now emerging.
</P>
<P>
The institute urged the U.S. to lead in restructuring economy.
"If the United States does not lead, the world economy will suffer
as its ecological base deteriorates," it stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
