<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Law to Ban Cloning of Humans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today urged Congress to make laws to ban cloning of humans and
described a Chicago physicist's intention to clone humans as
"unsafe and morally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
"It's now clearer than ever the legislation is exactly what is
needed," the president said in his weekly radio address to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Independent scientist Richard Seed announced last Wednesday
that he would soon begin work on human cloning.
</P>
<P>
The news has brought public concerns. Clinton said it was
"profoundly troubling."
</P>
<P>
After Scottish scientists cloned the adult sheep Dolly last
winter, Clinton sent Congress a bill to ban the use of similar
procedures to clone human beings.
</P>
<P>
Last March, the president issued an executive order banning use
of federal money for any such project.
</P>
<P>
"Personally, I believe that human cloning raises deep concerns
given our cherished concepts of faith and humanity," Clinton said
today. "Scientific advancement does not occur in a moral
vacuum.... We must move with caution, care and deep concern about
the impact of our actions."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "I call on Congress to act now to make it illegal,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
