<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Falls to Seven-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment rate
dropped in December to 8.6 percent for the first time in more than
seven years, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The drop ended a string of 86 months in which the rate was 9
percent or higher, the longest such stretch since Statistics
Canada began recording monthly job data 51 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In December, Canada's economy created 62,000 new jobs, more
than double the average monthly gains in the first 11 months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The December job gains brought Canada's total employment to
14.12 million on a seasonly adjusted basis, up 363,000 jobs from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest annual increase since 1994, which was the
best year of the 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
