<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Norwegian FMs See Dim Hope for Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that he agreed with Norwegian Foreign Minister
Knut Vollebaek who has just concluded a tour of Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas that the Mideast peace process has dim
hope.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he received a phone call from the Norwegian foreign
minister who "wanted to express his view that he saw no hope for
the future of the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
"I share this view, too," said the Egyptian top diplomat,
adding that matters are not proceeding in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek, when in Israel, urged the Jewish state to take
measures to move the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Norway had been actively involved in formulating the Oslo
Accords between the Israeli and Palestine Liberation Organization
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat will visit Egypt on January 19 to exchange
viewpoints on the current Mideast situation.
</P>
<P>
On the upcoming meetings U.S. President Bill Clinton will hold
with Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister, Moussa said the Washington
meetings were still standing.
</P>
<P>
"They represent the only remaining opportunity before reaching
a state of utter frustration," he added.
</P>
<P>
He called upon all parties concerned to consult on future plans
if the situation collapsed due to Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that Israel has adopted a certain ideological stance,
namely no to return of land, no to Madrid peace conference and no
to UN resolutions, which are all matters that we reject," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked since
last March when Israel began building a new settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
