<HEADLINE> EU to Send Mission to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 10 (Xinhua) -- The 15 member nations of the
European Union (EU) have agreed to send a mission to Algeria very
soon to consider how to help the country put an end to recent
massacres of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Experts on the Maghreb reached the agreement recently at a
meeting of the European Council of Ministers in Brussels, said
European Report, a twice-weekly newsletter published here today.
</P>
<P>
The council's political directors are scheduled to meet on
January 13 and will take the final decision as to whether to send
a European troika, composed by representatives of the current,
previous and upcoming EU presidencies.
</P>
<P>
The EU said the goal of the mission was not to investigate, but
simply to gather information.
</P>
<P>
Algiers, which described all foreign bids for investigation or
mediation as "unacceptable interference," has agreed to the
European experts' visit on the condition that they are limited to
discussing "cooperation in the fight against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Algerian Minister of Foreign Affairs Ahmed Attaf said in
Algiers Thursday that the troika's visit, which had been initiated
by Germany, was "welcome." Its purpose was to "step up the fight
against terrorism and Euro-Algerian cooperation in this area," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Attaf said the state was fighting terrorism by legitimate
means. "There is no confusion or doubt necessitating an
investigation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
