<HEADLINE> Jordan Pledges Maximum Efforts for Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam Majali today pledged maximum efforts by his government to
push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with visiting former U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz, Majali said that Jordan will exert maximum efforts
on regional and international levels to help end the current
stalemate in the peace process, Jordan's official news agency
Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian prime minister expressed the hope that the
intensive efforts being made by Jordan and other parties will
contribute to overcoming the obstacles facing the peace process
and reactivate negotiations on all tracks.
</P>
<P>
Majali also noted that the peace between Jordan and Israel is
an important part of a comprehensive regional peace.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Shultz commended Jordan's "pivotal" role in the
peace process, saying that the importance of Jordan's role
increased in the past years, especially after Jordan signed its
peace treaty with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Shultz is on a regional tour which also includes Syria, Israel
and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
