<HEADLINE> European Economic Outlook Remains Good: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 10 (Xinhua) -- In spite of the crisis on the
Asian markets, the economic outlook in Europe continues to inspire
confidence, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The economic sentiment indicator fell from 103.5 to 103.0, but
this is mainly attributed to a decline in stock prices, European
Report, a twice-weekly newsletter published here today, quoted an
economic survey by the European Union (EU)'s executive body, the
European Commission, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The industrial confidence indicator for Europe remained at the
same high level in November as in October though stock markets
reported a decline in all EU member states between the two months.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that while confidence among consumers
remained unchanged, confidence in the retail trade sector improved
and remained above its 10-year average.
</P>
<P>
The positive climate reflected in the economic sentiment
indicator in the EU is also apparent in the leading indicator for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Questioned in October about the most serious problems affecting
their domestic economies, European economic experts again placed
unemployment at the top of the list, with budget deficits coming
second, which is also the case for the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Lack of confidence in government policy and weak demand ranked
third and fourth at world level, while they were given equal
importance at EU level.
</P>
<P>
The ranking of the problems has reportedly barely altered since
the April survey, the exception being that in Europe inflation is
now being considered a more important problem than foreign
indebtedness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
