<HEADLINE> Republican Senator Rejects Clinton's Child Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Republican Senator Larry
Craig today criticized U.S. President Bill Clinton's plan to
expand federally funded child care programs, saying parents want
choices and "don't want the federal government telling them what
they need."
</P>
<P>
In the Republicans' weekly radio address today, Craig said the
government "should not discriminate against parents who decide to
stay home." He suggested that mothers or fathers who take care of
their own families should also be given benefits from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Clinton unveiled a 21.7 billion-dollar,
five-year child care initiative. The proposal would double to more
than 2 million the number of children receiving care subsidies and
increase tax credits for 3 million working families.
</P>
<P>
Craig said he was disappointed by the proposal and it would be
in addition to about 14 billion dollars the federal government is
already spending on child care.
</P>
<P>
Craig said, "What every family does not need is the government
telling them what is best or giving them a one-size-fits-all
solution. Congressional Republicans believe the best way to help
American families care for their children is to provide as many
options as possible and leave more money in their pockets, not
launder it through countless federal programs that shrink every
dollar they earn."
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised to discuss his child care initiative further
in his State of the Union address later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
